  "summaries": [
    {
      "id": "summary:abstract",
      "type": "abstract",
      "value": "McKnight's encoded selection joins four anonymous Middle English verse works. Dame Siriz is a fabliau of clerical courtship, a go-between, and manufactured adultery; the fragmentary Interludium presents a clerk's courtship dialogue and mediation by an old woman; The Fox and Wolf in the Well is a beast fable of appetite and trickery; and Sir Cleges is a Christmas romance in which generosity brings poverty, miraculous cherries restore a displaced knight, and a comic reward of twelve blows exposes corrupt gatekeepers.",
      "language": "eng",
      "scope": {
        "kind": "whole"
      },
      "evidence_ids": [
        "evidence:metadata-xml-computation",
        "evidence:metadata-mcknight-edition"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "summary:cataloging-scope",
      "type": "cataloging_note",
      "value": "The source XML preserves the edition title page and the four work texts on printed pages 1–59, with McKnight's textual notes, while omitting the substantive preface, introduction, bibliography, explanatory notes, glossary, and other front and back matter. Dame Siriz and the Interludium are nested under one top-level poem DIV1, but the latter remains an independent work. The XML contains 1,406 L elements; the conventional total is 1,405 verse lines because the Interludium's Latin speaker formula is encoded as one additional L element.",
      "language": "eng",
      "scope": {
